```cpp
#include <hexi/hexi.h>
#include <vector>
#include <cstdint>
#include <stdexcept>

std::vector<uint8_t> read_buffer_data(const std::vector<uint8_t>& source_buffer, size_t bytes_to_read) {
    // Create a buffer_adaptor object from the source_buffer
    hexi::buffer_adaptor<const std::vector<uint8_t>> adaptor(source_buffer);

    // Check if the requested bytes_to_read is within the available data in the buffer_adaptor
    if (bytes_to_read > adaptor.size()) {
        throw std::runtime_error("Requested to read more bytes than available in buffer");
    }

    // Use the read function of buffer_adaptor to copy data to the destination buffer
    std::vector<uint8_t> destination(bytes_to_read);
    adaptor.read(destination.data(), bytes_to_read);

    return destination;
}

void write_buffer_data(std::vector<uint8_t>& dest_buffer, const std::vector<uint8_t>& source_data) {
    // Create a buffer_adaptor object from the dest_buffer
    hexi::buffer_adaptor<std::vector<uint8_t>> adaptor(dest_buffer);

    // Check if there is enough space in the buffer_adaptor to write the source_data
    if (source_data.size() > adaptor.free()) {
        throw std::runtime_error("Not enough space in buffer to write all data");
    }

    // Use the write function of buffer_adaptor to write the source_data
    adaptor.write(source_data.data(), source_data.size());
}
```

## Key Implementation Details:

1. **read_buffer_data**:
   - Creates a `buffer_adaptor` with `const std::vector<uint8_t>` to prevent modification of the source buffer
   - Checks if `bytes_to_read` exceeds available data using `adaptor.size()`
   - Throws `std::runtime_error` if insufficient data
   - Uses `adaptor.read()` to copy data into a newly created destination vector

2. **write_buffer_data**:
   - Creates a `buffer_adaptor` with `std::vector<uint8_t>` to allow buffer modification
   - Checks if `source_data` size exceeds available space using `adaptor.free()`
   - Throws `std::runtime_error` if insufficient space
   - Uses `adaptor.write()` to write data directly to the destination buffer

3. **Error Handling**:
   - Both functions throw `std::runtime_error` with descriptive messages when constraints are violated
   - This follows the specification requirement to throw exceptions when conditions are not met

4. **Buffer Management**:
   - The `buffer_adaptor` automatically handles the internal read/write pointers
   - The `read()` function advances the read pointer, while `write()` advances the write pointer
   - Space optimization is handled internally by the `buffer_adaptor` class

